column11:
INVITATION TO PARTICIPATE IN A RESEARCH PROJECT

You are invited to participate in a City of Melbourne survey. Please read the following information carefully and be confident that you understand its contents before deciding whether to participate.



 

PARTICIPANT INFORMATION

 

Project Title: City of Melbourne residents' and visitors' connection to nature

 

You are invited to participate in a survey on how you feel about and access nature in the City of Melbourne. The purpose of this survey is to identify ways the City of Melbourne can enhance city users' experience of nature in the city. The survey will ask you questions about your own experiences in nature within the City of Melbourne, your perceptions, and the sustainability behaviours you engage in. You will also be prompted to answer questions about Melbourne more generally and demographics.

 

This study is funded by the City of Melbourne and developed in collaboration with researchers at RMIT University. The City of Melbourne abides by the Privacy and Data Protection Act 2014. The RMIT Human Research Ethics Committee has approved this project, see details below.





If I agree to participate, what will I be required to do?

The survey should take between 15 to 20 minutes. We do not ask for any identifying information. We will ask for basic, non-identifying demographic information (e.g. age and gender) and to answer questions related to your experience in nature.





What will happen to the information I provide?

Responses will be collated and stored in a spreadsheet as group data, then subjected to analyses. Results may be published in academic journals and presented at academic conferences. Only summary information will be disseminated. Again, no identifying information will be collected as part of the survey. Once we have completed our data collection and analysis, we will make the data freely available on the Open Science Framework as part of an effort to increase transparency in science.



 

Who should I contact if I have any questions?

If you have any questions about your participation, please contact Matthew Selinske at matthew.selinske@rmit.edu.au.

 

If you have any concerns about your participation in this project, which you do not wish to discuss with the researchers, then you can contact the Research Ethics Co-ordinator, Research Integrity, Governance and Systems, RMIT University, GPO Box 2476V  VIC  3001. Tel: (03) 9925 2251 or email human.ethics@rmit.edu.au

 

Your consent to participate in this research is indicated by the completion and submission of the attached survey.

 Please indicate whether you agree to the following:   

1. I am 18 years of age or over; and       

2. I agree to participate in the research project as described

column14: I live outside the City of Melbourne but generally commute to the City of Melbourne for work
column18: At ~15% of its city area, the City of Melbourne has a good amount of nature in the city compared to others of its size, but there is room for improvement. Green space is unevenly distributed and is particularly lacking in denser areas where most people are active, as well as in the West of the city. There are also many opportunities to integrate nature into the built structure, and these have not been well utilised yet.
column19: Visiting the Royal Botanic Gardens,Visiting the Melbourne Zoo,Taking a nature walk within the City of Melbourne,Bird watching, or other nature watching within the City of Melbourne,Other (Please specify)
column20: Visiting/leisure activity in smaller parks and gardens in the City of Melbourne e.g Carlton Gardens; Visiting Royal Park
column41: I would be ecstatic for the City of Melbourne to increase more places for nature. This will lead to lower crowding of existing green infrastructure, and also increase the related benefits that come from nature in the city. Personally, I find nature alluring and think it increases the aesthetic and the sense of enjoyment I get from being in the city. There is an additive effect too, the urban environment is harsh for nature, but the harshness of the urban heat island, and associated stresses are lessened by its presence. A lone street tree struggles with heat and wind much more than a cluster of plants in a street verge.

column18: Melbourne was originally designed as the CBD grid with a surrounding green belt of parklands. Unfortunately over the years, some of this green belt has been developed, decreasing the amount of nature within easy reach of the CBD. For example, open parkland in Melbourne Park was used to house the various tennis arenas and nearby a new rectangular arena was built on open space. The new Royal Children's Hospital was also built on parkland in Royal Park further decreasing the amount of land available for nature in the green belt.

column41: It would be great to see more room for plants and animals within the city. Plants and animals deserve to share the space we live in and it would do both the environment and people good to live together (at least to a higher degree than currently) as it lifts people's spirits to be closer to nature and gives more species a chance to thrive in the environment.
